track_notes: Good parking space at the end of the road. Cross dam, head along lake shore over stile.  Strike diagonally uphill, initially awkward boulders and bracken. Soon gives way to better going after crossing broken wall. Easier uphill ground leads to vehicle track. Through gate and turn left up hill to reach high wall at gate. Easy slopes to reach a final stile just before the summit.

Follow the pretty old path through the woods above Aberglaslyn Hall. The path is clear but slippery - lots of ancient moss. When you exit the woods the path starts to get indistinct. Follow the wall as best you can, but you will be tracking through bracken and getting wet feet. Pass the iron age hill fort of Pen-y-Gaer.

As the terrain levels at the top of Cwm Oerddwr head west of the old dams and then to the wall running north-south. The PRoW is over the stile but I took a short cut to the east side of the wall.

At the top of the valley between the twin summits a stile crosses the wall to the nothern summit. The AZ extends to both.

This route was hard because of the bracken and took nearly twice as long as expected. Geralds route will be far easier!

NT car park and Welsh Highland Railway halt at Nantmor provide a start/finish point.

Start point at SH58914215, A498 north of Prenteg. Pleasant woodland path, leads to pasture and Gorllwyn ruined farmhouse. Past Tai Cochion head right up hill. No way over wall at SH57744375, PRoW is fictional, so keep going and loop around the top. Turn right towards bwlch. Contour round to final ascent between twin summits, or as I did, follow track to south summit, drop down and back up the north summit.

2 hours in ascent.

Park near Llyn Cwmystradllyn and follow easy track to quarry. This is the former Gorseddau Railway which came from Porthmadog. Find a safe way across the quarry and head steeply uphill, joining other paths.
Same start as Geralds but following the shore further around Llyn Cymystradllyn along PRoW.
